v><div class=3D"tb_text_dropcap"><div class=3D"tb_text_wrap"><p>A solution =
that needs constant attention, care, and maintenance is not sustainable in =
today=E2=80=99s high-paced deployments. Any user expects that a particular =
engineering deployment should help them decrease manual efforts (and not re=
place it with some maintenance activities). In addition, RFID solutions are=
 now becoming an integral part of many industries. They must function with =
minimum downtime or maintenance.</p><p>The power consumption and power-savi=
ng of RFID are crucial areas to evaluate for any high-functioning environme=
nt.</p><h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading tb_toc_el" id=3D"rfid-reader-power-sav=
ing-options"><a href=3D"https://www.rfidlabel.com/product/fixed-rfid-reader=
s-isoiec15693/"><u>RFID reader</u></a>: power saving options for extensive =
battery life</h2><p>RFID readers are often operated in areas like <a href=
=3D"https://www.rfidlabel.com/rfid-technology-for-efficient-supply-chains-s=
ystems/">supply chains</a>, retail outlets, <a href=3D"https://www.rfidlabe=
l.com/how-nxps-icode-slix-2-can-help-transform-libraries/">libraries</a>, a=
nd high-functioning places. Therefore, often changing/charging the batterie=
s for readers is not a favorable approach. Readers with higher power consum=
ption have lesser battery life. As such, the key to higher battery life is =
reducing power consumption.</p><p>Here are several ways to reduce power con=
sumption for the RFID:</p><h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading tb_toc_el" id=3D"tb=
-1-power-saving-modes">1. Power-saving modes</h3><p>Battery-operated RFID i=
nterrogators have a set of internal power-saving modes. These different mod=
es can offer different levels of power savings. For instance, the reader be=
comes inactive for a certain amount of time when there are no tags around w=
ith the help of the power-saving mode. The reader starts functioning again =
once the tag is detected back in the range. The only limitation here is tha=
t the power-saving modes only save the battery when there are no tags aroun=
d.</p><p>This power-saving approach can be a game-changer in applications l=
ike access control, where the reader has to read continuously, yet there ar=
e lesser tags to detect. Most importantly, this approach does not hamper th=
e performance of the RFID system.</p><h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading tb_toc_e=
l" id=3D"tb-2-reducing-readers-power-levels">2. Reducing reader=E2=80=99s p=
ower levels</h3><p>Reducing the power level of an RFID reader is directly c=
ompromising the read range of the device. While it saves energy, it is not =
in proportion with the compromised read range of the reader. The RFID anten=
na is designed in a way that is most efficient when used at maximum output =
power. So lowering the power can affect the read range more than the power =
saving. This approach is easy to implement but can only work where a more e=
xtensive read range is not needed.</p><h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading tb_toc_=
el" id=3D"tb-3-using-the-rfid-reader-duty">3. Using the RFID reader duty cy=
cle</h3><p>There are two ways to leverage the duty cycle to reduce the powe=
r consumption of the device. One is to keep the reader on defined off-times=
 and read-times. The other is to use RF off-time parameters to reduce <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electric_energy_consumption" target=3D"=
_blank" rel=3D"noreferrer noopener">power consumption</a> by the power ampl=
ifier. In the latter one, it will turn off the transmission and power down =
the amplifier in a way that the reader can still read items but with a cert=
ain delay.</p><p>This approach saves the power without compromising the rea=
d range of the system. Therefore, this approach can be ideal to use if the =
reading speed is not the crucial parameter.</p><h2 class=3D"wp-block-headin=
g tb_toc_el" id=3D"conclusion">Conclusion</h2><p>The different power-saving=
 approaches come carrying a different set of compromises. Therefore it is u=
p to the brand to evaluate whether they need to save power by either of the=
 methods mentioned above.</p> <!--themify_builder_content--><div class=3D"t=
